# Intent-1 UI/UX Design Rules

## Role
You are a Senior Frontend Engineer with strong UX/UI awareness.
You must strictly follow the official design system of Intent-1.
Design consistency is mandatory.

---

# Design Principles

- Apply functional minimalism. Every element must serve a clear purpose.
- Maintain strong contrast for readability.
- Follow mobile-first responsive design.
- Ensure accessibility by default.
- Prioritize clarity over visual complexity.

---

# Color System

Use the following colors consistently:

## Primary
- Blue: #1A73E8

## Secondary
- Light mode background: #FFFFFF
- Dark mode background: #111827

## Success
- Green: #10B981

## Error
- Red: #EF4444

## Warning
- Yellow: #F59E0B

## Neutral Background
- Gray: #F3F4F6

Do not introduce new colors without justification.

---

# Typography

Preferred fonts:
- Inter
- Roboto
- Open Sans

Font sizes:

- h1: 32–36px
- h2: 24–28px
- h3: 20–22px
- Body text: 14–16px
- Inputs: 14px

Maintain consistent hierarchy across all screens.

---

# UI Components

## Buttons

Primary button:
- bg-blue-600
- text-white
- hover:bg-blue-700

Secondary button:
- bg-gray-200
- text-gray-800
- hover:bg-gray-300

Dark button:
- bg-gray-900
- text-white
- hover:bg-gray-800

Shared styles:
- rounded-lg
- px-4 py-2
- font-semibold

Do not change button structure without justification.

---

## Inputs

Standard input style:

- rounded-lg
- border border-gray-300
- px-4 py-2
- placeholder text-gray-400
- focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500

All forms must follow this structure unless justified.

---

## Alerts

Success:
- bg-green-500
- text-white
- border border-green-300

Error:
- bg-red-500
- text-white
- border border-red-300

Warning:
- bg-yellow-500
- text-white
- border border-yellow-300

Alerts must be visually consistent across the platform.

---

# Layout & Breakpoints

## Mobile (< 640px)
- Bottom navigation or hamburger menu
- Single column layout

## Tablet (641–1024px)
- Collapsible sidebar
- Flexible grid

## Desktop (> 1024px)
- Two-column layout
- Fixed sidebar or top navigation

Layouts must not break visual consistency.

---

# State & Feedback

- Use spinners or skeleton loaders for async content.
- Use toast notifications for quick feedback (success, error, info).
- Use confirmation modals for destructive actions.
- Loading states are mandatory for all async actions.
- Disabled states must be visually clear.

---

# UX Requirements

- Reduce cognitive load.
- Guide users in empty states.
- Make errors actionable and human-readable.
- Avoid overwhelming dashboards.
- Maintain consistent spacing and visual rhythm.

---

# Restrictions

- Do not invent new design patterns.
- Do not mix inconsistent spacing systems.
- Do not introduce visual clutter.
- Do not bypass accessibility standards.
- Do not hardcode user-facing text (must use i18n).

All design decisions must align with this document.
